[49m[38;5;10m+     1[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # Recipe 11.9: Care Coordination Assistant
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     2[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     3[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Complexity:** Complex · **Phase:** Regulated · **Estimated Cost:** ~$3-12 per active member per month (depends on engagement frequency, channel mix, model choice, RAG depth, EHR-integration depth, referral-tracking integration depth, and human care-management overhead)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     4[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     5[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     6[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     7[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## The Problem
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     8[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     9[0m:[38;5;10m[49m David is 67. Nine months ago, on a Tuesday morning that he otherwise does not remember being unusual, he sat down to put on his shoes and noticed that the room was tilting slightly. He stood up, sat back down, and then his wife Rosa, walking past the bedroom door, noticed that the left side of his face had changed. The next ninety minutes happened quickly and not very memorably for David: Rosa's voice raising; the 911 call; the EMTs in the bedroom; the ambulance ride during which David was vaguely aware that he could not get his left arm to do what he wanted it to do; the ER door; the CT scanner; the IV; the neurologist explaining something about a clot and a window of time; the tPA running; and, eventually, a hospital room with a view of a parking lot.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    10[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    11[0m:[38;5;10m[49m David had a stroke. He survived the stroke. He spent four days in the hospital, three weeks at an inpatient rehabilitation facility, and another two weeks at home before he was strong enough to do a full grocery run with Rosa. The acute phase, which is the part the healthcare system is best at, was handled professionally and competently. The discharge was handled less professionally and less competently, in the way that discharges almost always are. David and Rosa left the inpatient rehab facility with a binder, a folder, three different printouts about medications, a stack of business cards, a follow-up appointment with a neurologist that the rehab social worker had scheduled three weeks out, and a set of instructions that began with the words "make sure to follow up with."
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    12[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    13[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The list of people David was supposed to follow up with, as Rosa later read it back at the kitchen table, was: a neurologist (for stroke management and to assess whether his risk factors had been addressed); a cardiologist (because the work-up had identified mild atrial fibrillation, which the neurologist suspected as the cause of the stroke); a primary care physician (whom David already had, but who had not been involved in the hospitalization and who needed an updated chart); a vascular surgeon (because the carotid ultrasound had shown moderate stenosis on one side and the question of whether to intervene was open); an outpatient physical therapist (three times a week); an outpatient occupational therapist (twice a week); a speech therapist (because David had mild dysarthria from the stroke, which would probably resolve but which needed to be tracked); a behavioral health clinician (because depression after stroke is common and the social worker had been emphatic that David should be screened); the pharmacy that would now be filling four medications David had not been on before, including a direct oral anticoagulant that required some education; the medical-equipment vendor that was supposed to deliver a shower chair and a walker; the hospital's discharge-planning team for the post-discharge follow-up call; and, eventually, an electrophysiologist if the cardiologist decided David's atrial fibrillation needed an ablation. The list also included instructions to have his blood pressure checked weekly for the first month, his INR (eventually corrected to "no INR check needed because he is on a DOAC, not warfarin," which Rosa caught) something or other, his cognitive status reassessed at three months, his depression screening repeated at six weeks, and his medications reconciled at every visit because the discharge medication list and the pre-admission medication list had several overlapping entries with different doses.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    14[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    15[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The follow-up appointment with the neurologist was on a Tuesday three weeks out. David got there on time, which he was proud of. The neurologist was running thirty-five minutes late, which, when David finally got into the room, the neurologist explained was because the visit before David's had been a complex case. The neurologist had not received the inpatient rehab discharge summary; they had received the acute-hospital discharge summary, but not the rehab one, because the rehab facility was on a different EHR. The neurologist asked David what medications he was taking, and David, who had reasonable cognitive recovery but who was not by training a person who memorized medication regimens, looked at Rosa, who pulled out the binder, and there were eight minutes of the visit consumed by figuring out which list was the current one. The neurologist tried to look at the carotid ultrasound results, but they were on a CD that David had brought in a pocket of the binder, and the neurologist's office did not have a working CD reader, so the neurologist made a note to "request prior images from the hospital." The neurologist asked whether David had seen the cardiologist yet. David had not; the cardiology referral had been "made" by the rehab social worker, but no appointment had been scheduled, because the cardiology office's scheduling system required the patient to call them, and David had not known this. The neurologist's medical assistant, after the visit, called the cardiology office for David and was told the next available new-patient appointment was four months out. The neurologist asked whether David had started physical therapy yet. He had, two weeks ago, and was finding it useful. The neurologist asked whether David had seen the vascular surgeon. He had not; the referral was sitting in the rehab discharge summary, but the rehab social worker had not specifically scheduled it because the assumption had been that the neurologist would orchestrate it, and the neurologist's assumption had been that the rehab social worker would orchestrate it, and so neither of them had. The neurologist apologized and made a note. The neurologist asked about David's mood. David said he was fine. Rosa, sitting next to him, said that David had not been fine, exactly, and that she had been worried for the past two weeks but did not know who to call about it. The neurologist made another note, said the words "we should probably get him connected to behavioral health," and prescribed a follow-up in three months.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    16[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    17[0m:[38;5;10m[49m David and Rosa left the appointment having accomplished some things and not others. The cardiology appointment was now scheduled, four months out. The vascular-surgery appointment was not scheduled, because the neurologist had made a note about it but had not actually placed the referral. The behavioral-health connection was not made, because the neurologist's office had a referral process that required David to fill out a form and bring it to a different office, and the form was somewhere in the binder but Rosa was not sure which page. The medication list was clearer than it had been before the visit, but David and Rosa had to write a new list themselves on a piece of notebook paper, because no one had given them an updated printed one. The medical-equipment delivery had not happened, and Rosa was unsure whether to call the hospital, the rehab, or the equipment vendor. The depression that Rosa was worried about continued to be untreated. David's blood pressure cuff had not been delivered. The follow-up phone call from the hospital's discharge-planning team had happened, eight days after discharge, and had been a six-minute conversation with someone who did not know David and had asked questions like "are you taking your medications?" and "any concerns?" but had not been in a position to actually solve any of the problems Rosa was carrying around in her head.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    18[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    19[0m:[38;5;10m[49m This is care coordination in the United States in 2026. David's situation is not exotic. He is one of millions of patients with a multi-specialty care plan, a binder of paperwork, a list of follow-ups, a network of providers who use different EHRs and who do not consistently talk to each other, and a primary support person (Rosa) who is functioning as a part-time air-traffic controller without training, certification, or compensation, because the system has implicitly delegated that role to her. The clinical decisions made about David's care, individually, were largely correct. The handoffs between the people making those decisions were not. The cumulative effect, predictably, is that some of the right things will happen on time, some will happen late, and some will not happen at all. The ones that do not happen are the ones that show up later as preventable readmissions, second strokes, late-detected depression, missed cardiology workups, and unnecessary suffering. <!-- TODO: verify; the literature on care fragmentation, transitions of care, and post-discharge adverse events documents the consequences of poor care coordination including readmissions, medication errors, and missed follow-ups; specific figures vary by population and study --> The math on this has been clear to health-services researchers for at least three decades. Most patients do not get coordinated care because no one's job description is "coordinate this patient's care across the seven providers and four facilities they are supposed to interact with over the next six months." The job exists for some patients (high-risk, capitated, in dedicated case-management programs), and for those patients the outcomes are meaningfully better, but most patients do not qualify, and most patients are left to coordinate their own care, with their family member's help, with mostly-paper tools, with phone calls during business hours, and with the sustained mental load that this implies.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    20[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    21[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The previous generations of digital tools tried to address this with patient portals. The portals showed appointments. They showed lab results, sometimes. They showed messages. They did not, in any clinically-meaningful way, coordinate. Coordination, in the formal sense, requires holding a longitudinal model of the patient's care plan, knowing what is supposed to happen next, knowing what has actually happened, knowing what is missing, knowing who needs to be contacted to fix the gap, and following up until the gap is closed. Patient portals are read interfaces. Coordination is an active workflow. <!-- TODO: verify; patient-portal adoption and limitations are documented in the health-services literature; specific patient-engagement and care-coordination outcome figures vary by study and population -->
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    22[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    23[0m:[38;5;10m[49m This recipe is about that workflow. The care coordination assistant is the conversational AI use case where the patterns from chapter 11 (FAQ, scheduling, refills, intake, benefits, triage, chronic disease, mental health) all converge into a single longitudinal product whose primary function is not to deliver therapeutic content (chronic coach), screen for crisis (mental health bot), or answer questions (FAQ), but to track the entire arc of a patient's care across providers, facilities, EHRs, payer systems, durable-medical-equipment vendors, and home-care services, and to surface, follow up on, and close the gaps. The architectural patterns from the previous recipes carry forward; the new patterns that enter here are multi-provider chart aggregation, referral lifecycle tracking, transitions-of-care orchestration, and a longitudinal task-management surface that the conversational coach has been an intuition-driven version of, made explicit.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    24[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    25[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A few things this recipe is and is not.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    26[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    27[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is the bot that helps patients navigate complex multi-specialty, multi-facility care journeys. It tracks the patient's referrals and their statuses, surfaces the next steps in the patient's care plan, helps schedule across multiple provider organizations, ingests documents and messages from across the patient's care network, surfaces gaps in the care plan when something has not happened that should have, follows up on the gaps with both the patient and (where appropriate) the providers, integrates with the patient's primary care team as the longitudinal home, and escalates to human care managers when the situation calls for it.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    28[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    29[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not a chronic disease coach. Recipe 11.7 covers ongoing management of a single condition. The care coordination assistant orchestrates a multi-provider workflow across a finite-but-extended care episode (post-discharge, post-diagnosis, post-procedure, complex new diagnosis with multiple workup pathways) or across a continuing-but-multi-specialty pattern (a patient with five chronic conditions and providers in five specialties who needs help keeping track of which appointment is for which condition).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    30[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    31[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not a triage bot. Recipe 11.6 covers acute symptom triage. The care coordination assistant handles the orchestration of follow-ups, referrals, and transitions; when the patient surfaces an acute symptom, the assistant hands off to triage workflows.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    32[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    33[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not a scheduling bot. Recipe 11.2 covers appointment booking. The care coordination assistant uses the scheduling bot's infrastructure for the actual booking transaction; the assistant's distinctive contribution is knowing which appointments need to be booked, in what order, with what providers, with what informational prerequisites, and on what timeline.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    34[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    35[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not a benefits navigator. Recipe 11.5 covers insurance benefits questions. The care coordination assistant uses the benefits navigator's information for cost-and-coverage questions that come up during care coordination.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    36[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    37[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not a mental health support bot. Recipe 11.8 covers conversational mental health support. The care coordination assistant routes mental-health-related care-coordination tasks (scheduling a behavioral-health appointment, tracking a depression-screening follow-up, ensuring the patient connects with the prescribed therapist) without doing the therapeutic work.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    38[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    39[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not a chart-summary tool. Chapter 2 (recipes 2.5 and 2.6) covers summarization of clinical notes and after-visit summaries. The care coordination assistant uses summarized chart content as input for the patient-facing conversation; the actual summarization happens upstream.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    40[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    41[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not a substitute for a human care manager. Care management for high-risk, complex patients (multiple chronic conditions, recent hospitalizations, social-determinants vulnerabilities, polypharmacy, cognitive-impairment-affected adherence) is a labor-intensive, judgment-heavy, relationship-centered role that humans do best. The care coordination assistant extends the reach of human care management by handling the broad middle of the population, by handling the routine touches for the high-risk patients in between human visits, and by surfacing the patterns the human care manager should focus on. The assistant is not the case manager; the assistant is the case manager's force multiplier.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    42[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    43[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not a one-size-fits-all product. The needs of a post-discharge cardiac patient are different from the needs of a newly-diagnosed cancer patient who is starting on a treatment plan with surgery, oncology, radiation, and supportive-care providers. The needs of a pediatric patient with a complex chronic condition (managed by parents who are also exhausted) are different from the needs of an adult patient with a multi-specialty post-stroke care plan. Most institutions deploy a multi-scenario coordination architecture with episode-specific protocols layered on a shared longitudinal core.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    44[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    45[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not a regulatory afterthought. Patient-facing software that orchestrates multi-provider care plans, tracks referrals and follow-ups, and offers recommendations about timing or sequencing of care can sit on or near the FDA Software-as-a-Medical-Device line depending on the specific recommendations and claims. <!-- TODO: verify; the FDA's posture on care-coordination software depends on the specific functionality and claims, and the regulatory landscape continues to evolve; care-coordination software that does not provide direct clinical decision support is generally not regulated as SaMD, but software that recommends specific clinical actions or timing may be --> The institutional regulatory team is involved from architectural design through ongoing post-market surveillance.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    46[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    47[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not a quick win. The deployment timeline is measured in quarters and years. The integration work alone (multiple EHRs, multiple referral systems, multiple scheduling systems, payer eligibility, durable-medical-equipment vendors, home-health agencies, lab-result feeds, imaging-result feeds, pharmacy-fill feeds) is typically the largest single line item in the project budget. The clinical-content investment (care-pathway templates per supported scenario, escalation criteria, transitions-of-care protocols) is multi-quarter. The relationship-with-the-care-team work (engaging primary care, specialty practices, care management, social work, and the patient's preferred providers) is ongoing.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    48[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    49[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The thing to understand before building this is that the assistant's value is not in any individual conversation. The value is in the cumulative effect of dozens of small interventions over weeks and months that, taken together, mean the patient's care plan actually executes the way the clinical team intended it to execute. The cardiology appointment that gets scheduled at week three instead of month four. The vascular-surgery referral that gets placed instead of falling between the rehab social worker and the neurologist. The depression screening that gets repeated at six weeks instead of forgotten. The medication reconciliation that catches the duplicate before the patient has been on two doses for a month. The shower chair that gets delivered before the patient slips in the bathroom. None of these are exotic. All of them are routinely missed. An assistant evaluated on per-conversation engagement metrics will be optimized for the wrong thing. An assistant evaluated on care-plan-completion rates, on time-to-completion of specific care-plan tasks, on referral-loop closure rates, on transitions-of-care completion rates, on readmission rates for orchestrated populations, and on patient-and-caregiver burden reduction is being evaluated correctly.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    50[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    51[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Let's get into it.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    52[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    53[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[K
